	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />Yeah, that must be another version of the willem.org burner.  It does seem kinda expensive for it not including a ZIF socket (those cost probably $5-$10 and the cheaper one I bought to mess with needs huge holes on the board).  You won't need the PLCC-to-DIP adapters for NES probably, you won't find too many carts that use PLCC sockets.  I got my burner from sivava.com (Thailand), it seemed to be the cheapest one (~$50) and came with a few adapters.
<br />
<br />If you can spend about $100-$200 USD, I'd recommend getting an EPROM emulator.  For that price range I've seen new ones for 128kB-512kB, I can find the urls if you want to see them.  There's cheaper used ones around sometimes.  It connects to a cart's ROM socket, then to update the program you run an upload program on PC and reset the NES.  Swapping chips with an external programmer just takes lots of time.
<br />
<br />Or CopyNES, it's cheap as a kit but needs surgery on the NES (safely removing the CPU).  Then make a homemade RAM cart or one of these flashcart boards I'm making, once those work.
<br />
<br />Also, if you find the Squeedo cart interesting (assuming you know all about it, I haven't made a website for it yet), I'm looking for some testers that are actively developing stuff to loan one to.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
