		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" />The EPROM programmer on that website I mentioned is only for EPROM's 28 or 32 pin 27C64-27040, all you need for all NES EPROM's. It only has two IC's and is a fairly easy project. I made mine with a ZIF chip for convenience. If you're going to play around with NES hardware you have to do some soldering. This place is great for parts with very low S&amp;H:
<br />
<br /><!-- m --><a class="postlink" href="http://www.futurlec.com">http://www.futurlec.com</a><!-- m -->
<br />
<br />Only $5 to ship to Brazil. They ship in a little package which always gets delivered to my door without any customs or taxes. It's actually cheaper to buy the parts from them than to take the bus downtown and pay taxes and busfare.

		

