		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">No Carrier wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Actually, a ZIF or regular DIP socket will allow you to easily take chips in and out of the board. You don't have to solder them in every time.</div><br />So I can just install one of those on the cart? Wouldn't it be too bulky to fit on the console?<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">I'm looking into ways I can get you a programmer quickly.. I'll let you know how it goes. When do you need it?</div>
<br />Wow, I appreciate the help, but I don't want to cause you any trouble, ok? If we can arrange something I'd be more than happy, but if for any reason we can't, just relax. I don't need it for any specific time, I guess I'll do NES development forever! =) I'm just trying to improve my tools as I don't want to rely on emulators forever.
<br />
<br />Yesterday I got myself a NROM game (Spy vs Spy) and a SMB3 cart, as I may want to make a MMC3 devcart someday, when I'm more used to this. Spy vs Spy's connectors are not very clean and it takes some time for the game to work, but it does. I guess I can clean it up with no problems. I Hope this can become my first devcart.
<br />
<br />I managed to open the carts by heating the screws with a soldering iron while applying force to the cart. Works much better than the melted pen. I'll probably have to replace the screws, though. I was surprised to see that both SMB3 carts used different components from one another. One of the WRAM chips was manufactured by SANYO and the other by NEC. And the other chips were different also. My older SMB3 doesn't work, I have no idea why.
<br />
<br />No Carrier, I really appreciate your help, and I guess I can wait a little longer so I can decide what is the best I can get in spite of any difficulties and/or limitations.
<br />
<br />I'm reading about SQUEEDO now, and it seems very nice. Though I do like the idea of games running on standard boards too. Maybe I'll get both someday =)

		

